observations.recommendation:
a. Inventory committee to conduct complete physical inventory of PPE and render a report thereon;
b. Accounting and the Property Office to reconcile results of the physical inventory taking as reflected in the RPCPPE with their respective records;
c. Accounting Office to prepare the necessary adjusting entries for any discrepancies between the RPCPPE and the Schedule of PPE to present the correct balance of the PPE account; and
d. Accounting Office to consider the following entries to correct the currently understatement of the Accumulated Depreciation, the PPE and other affected accounts: i. To adjust the accumulated depreciation: (detailed entries provided in report) ii. To record PPEs found in the RPCPPE but not in the books of accounts (detailed entries) iii. To derecognize transferred Other PPEs to Barangays (detailed entries) iv. To reclassify improvement of the evacuation and multi-purpose ground to its proper account (detailed entries)

a. Inventory Committee to conduct an annual inventory of the local roads within the Municipality’s jurisdiction and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network;
b. General Service Officer or the Municipal Treasurer to prepare Report on Local Road Network (RLRN) and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
c. Engineering Office to provide the Municipal Accounting Office and the Municipal Treasurer’s Office the complete description and cost segregation of road components per project; and
d. Municipal Accounting Office to: i. prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation of each depreciable local road network component that will be sourced from the reports stated earlier; ii. provide adequate disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements with regard to the LRN account; and iii. maintain subsidiary ledgers for the Local Road Networks and its components.
iv. adjust the erroneous classification of Other Infrastructure Assets as LRN with the proposed entry.

a. timely implement the LDRRMFIP and optimize the utilization of its LDRRMF to lessen the socio-economic impacts of disasters, and to enhance disaster preparedness and response capabilities of the community;
b. transfer only the unexpended balance of DRRMF-MOOE and QRF to Special Trust Fund excluding Capital Outlay; and
c. ensure that LDRRMF be strictly appropriated and utilized only for the implementation of projects and activities for the prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response, and rehabilitation and recovery.

a. Conduct proper validation of identified or proposed projects to ensure that only feasible PPAs are included in the AIP;
b. Instruct the concerned Municipal Officials to closely monitor the implementation of the identified development projects especially those from previous years’ budgets; and
c. Set a timetable within which to start and complete the unimplemented projects.

a. Send another demand letters to the concerned NGOs/POs for the immediate submission of the Fund Utilization Report;
b. Proper monitoring and evaluation of the projects undertaken by the recipient NGOs/POs be made to determine that the funds were utilized for its intended purpose; and
c. Institute appropriate action against the defaulting NGOs/POs in case the demand letters are ignored pursuant to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2007-001.

a. Send demand letters to the NGOs/POs to immediately submit the liquidation reports and its supporting documents in compliance with the prescribed COA Circular Nos. 2007-001;
b. Reassess the feasibility of the unimplemented projects and fast tract its implementation, otherwise: a) return the funds to the respective source agencies for additional resources that could be put into better use of the other agencies needing assistance; and b) revert the unexpended balance of the Municipalitys’ counterpart to the General Fund for appropriation; and
c. Remit the unutilized balance of PDAF to the National Treasury in compliance with the Supreme Court Decision.

We reiterated the following prior years’ audit recommendations and management agreed to:
 Instruct the Municipal Accountant to verify the transactions involving the Due to Other Funds and Due from Other Funds accounts and make the necessary adjustments thereto, to eliminate/reconcile the accounts;
 Undertake periodic reconciliation so that the accounts are immediately adjusted in the books of accounts to ensure fair presentation in the financial statements.
